    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking at some Cessna maintenance docs. Can you explain the actual physics of how a pitot tube works to measure airspeed? Also, why is it such a big deal if the opening gets blocked?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A pitot tube measures dynamic air pressure by capturing the total pressure of the oncoming airflow. This total pressure is then converted into airspeed using the Bernoulli principle, which states that an increase in speed results in a decrease in pressure. If the opening is blocked, the tube cannot measure the true ram air pressure, causing the indicated airspeed to register far lower than the actual speed, which is a critical safety failure.",
      "source": "target",
